This survey will help you evaluate your current competency levels in core areas of instructional design. 

By answering questions related to different instructional design specializations, you'll gain insights into your strengths and identify potential growth areas. 

Discover where your skills shine and pinpoint sectors where you may want to focus your development to achieve your ideal instructional design career path. 

Click Start to begin.
You're designing training for employees who will primarily access it on their smartphones.  Which approach resonates most with you?
Focus on short, text-heavy lessons that can be quickly read, ensuring the core content is conveyed even on a small screen.
Design visually engaging modules with concise text, limited interactive elements, and short videos.
Prioritize compatibility across all devices, primarily using PDFs or slide decks that employees can download and access offline.

In the military and defense sector, Instructional Designers focus on developing highly specialized training programs to meet the unique needs of armed forces personnel. This includes tactical training, technical skills development, leadership programs, and simulations. The training materials must often support high-stakes environments and are designed to be rigorous, secure, and effective under diverse and challenging conditions. Instructional Designers in this area work closely with military experts to ensure the accuracy and relevance of the content, incorporating advanced technologies such as VR/AR for immersive learning experiences.
